


A Five-Scale Civilizational Model Language (CML)


GitHub Specification v1.0
Status: Draft Specification
License: Apache-2.0
Category: Systems Framework / Human & Collective Dynamics
Purpose: A common language for describing stability, adaptation, learning, and collapse across human, organizational, and civilizational systems.



1. Purpose
The Civilizational Model Language (CML) provides a deterministic framework for describing systems operating across multiple scales.
The framework is intended to:
Analyze system stability
Detect collapse mechanisms
Design adaptive learning structures
Improve feedback integrity
Provide a common vocabulary across disciplines
CML is descriptive first.
It does not require acceptance of any metaphysical assumptions.


2. Scope
CML applies to:
Individuals
Relationships
Teams
Organizations
Institutions
Nations
Civilizations
The model assumes that all persistent systems must continuously process:
information
feedback
challenge
adaptation



3. Core Definitions
3.1 Signal
A signal is any event capable of modifying system state.
Examples:
observation
message
interaction
environmental change
technological disruption
3.2 State
The complete condition of a system at a given moment.
Notation:

S(t)
where:
S = system state
t = time

3.3 Feedback
Feedback is information regarding the consequences of system behavior.
Feedback may be:
internal
external
immediate
delayed
3.4 Challenge
A challenge is any signal requiring adaptation.
Challenge is necessary for long-term system stability.
3.5 Collapse
Collapse is the loss of adaptive capacity.
A collapsed system:
no longer processes reality accurately
no longer adapts effectively
accumulates unresolved distortion



4. The Five Scales
Scale 1 — Signal Layer
Description
The instantaneous interaction layer.
Contains:
stimuli
events
observations
local interactions
Time Constant
Milliseconds to seconds.
Primary Question

What is happening now?
Failure Mode
Signal overload.
Scale 2 — Cognitive Layer
Description
Individual processing system.
Contains:
perception
memory
attention
learning
Time Constant
Seconds to years.
Primary Question

How is the signal interpreted?
Failure Modes
saturation
bias lock
unresolved memory accumulation
Scale 3 — Interaction Layer
Description
Two-agent or multi-agent dynamics.
Contains:
communication
trust
conflict
coordination
Time Constant
Minutes to decades.
Primary Question

How do systems influence each other?
Failure Modes
escalation loops
communication failure
synchronization loss
Scale 4 — Organizational Layer
Description
Structured coordination systems.
Examples:
companies
schools
governments
universities
Time Constant
Years to decades.
Primary Question

How is collective action organized?
Failure Modes
bureaucracy
incentive drift
latency accumulation
Scale 5 — Civilizational Layer
Description
Large-scale human systems.
Examples:
economies
cultures
nations
global infrastructure
Time Constant
Decades to centuries.
Primary Question

How does society remain adaptive?
Failure Modes
stagnation
systemic fragmentation
large-scale collapse



5. Cross-Scale Law
Principle
No scale operates independently.
Changes propagate upward and downward.

Signal
   ↓
Cognitive
   ↓
Interaction
   ↓
Organization
   ↓
Civilization
Distortion at any layer eventually affects the others.



6. Collapse Taxonomy
All collapse mechanisms are classified into six categories.
C1 — Information Saturation
Definition
Input exceeds integration capacity.
Symptoms
confusion
overload
decision paralysis
Examples
burnout
bureaucratic paperwork explosion
C2 — Reactive Lock
Definition
A single signal dominates system behavior.
Symptoms
tunnel vision
escalation
overreaction
Examples
panic
revenge cycles
crisis politics
C3 — Memory Override
Definition
Historical state dominates present observation.
Symptoms
rigidity
inability to update beliefs
institutional inertia
C4 — Challenge Deficiency
Definition
Insufficient adaptive pressure.
Symptoms
stagnation
skill decay
entropy drift
C5 — Feedback Separation
Definition
System loses contact with reality.
Symptoms
echo chambers
poor decisions
self-reinforcing narratives
C6 — Latency Collapse
Definition
Response speed slower than environmental change.
Symptoms
chronic crisis
obsolete structures
governance failure
7. Stability Law
A system remains stable when:

Adaptation Rate ≥ Environmental Change Rate
and

Feedback Integrity > Distortion Growth
8. Continuous Learning Principle
Definition
Learning is not accumulation.
Learning is:

Challenge
   →
Adaptation
   →
Integration
   →
Recovery
repeated continuously.
Stability Condition
Learning remains beneficial only when:

Challenge < Collapse Threshold
and

Recovery > Accumulated Stress
9. Anti-Collapse Architecture
A resilient system requires:
A1
Continuous feedback.
A2
Appropriate challenge.
A3
Recovery cycles.
A4
Low latency decision loops.
A5
Reality-based correction mechanisms.
10. Design Rules
Rule 1
Never optimize exclusively for stability.
Excessive stability causes stagnation.
Rule 2
Never optimize exclusively for challenge.
Excessive challenge causes breakdown.
Rule 3
Maintain feedback integrity.
Without feedback, adaptation stops.
Rule 4
Reduce latency wherever possible.
Delayed adaptation increases collapse probability.
Rule 5
Preserve learning indefinitely.
Adaptive systems remain viable longer than static systems.
11. Applications
Individuals
Personal development.
Education
Learning system design.
Organizations
Governance and management.
Public Policy
Institutional resilience.
Civilization
Long-term adaptive planning.
12. Reference Statement
The Civilizational Model Language proposes that:
Stability emerges from continuous adaptation across five interconnected scales, while collapse emerges from unresolved distortion, broken feedback, excessive latency, or insufficient challenge.
